Actually, I think this is wrong. The content-range-spec production
does not reference the more general range-unit, but instead uses
bytes-unit directly.

&gt; range-unit       = bytes-unit | other-range-unit
&gt; bytes-unit       = &quot;bytes&quot;
&gt; other-range-unit = token
&gt;
&gt;  The only range unit defined by HTTP/1.1 is &quot;bytes&quot;.
&gt; HTTP/1.1 implementations MAY ignore ranges specified using other units.
&gt;
&gt; HTTP/1.1 has been designed to allow implementations of applications that do
&gt; not depend on knowledge of ranges.

These words from the spec seem to be written with GET in mind, I&#39;m not
sure they make sense for PUT.

